          "body": "Leviticus 26 is not a standalone warning but the closing chapter of Israel's founding legal corpus. It occupies the structural position that Deuteronomy 28-30 will later occupy — the covenant's 'terms of engagement': this is what obedience secures, this is what rebellion forfeits. The ancient Near Eastern treaty parallels (Hittite suzerainty treaties from the second millennium BC) illuminate the form: Great King identifies himself, recites his benefits, states his demands, lists blessings and curses, and deposits the document in the sanctuary. Leviticus 26 follows this form almost exactly, making the treaty structure explicit at verse 46: 'these are the statutes and ordinances and laws which the LORD established between Himself and the sons of Israel through Moses at Mount Sinai.' To read Leviticus 26 as a list of rewards and punishments is to miss its genre — it is a covenant relationship document, and its tone is relational throughout. God does not issue curses as an angry sovereign; He escalates discipline as one trying to recover a partner who keeps walking away."
