          "title": "The blessings — creation restored (26:1-13)",
          "body": "The blessing section is a picture of creation functioning as God designed it: rains in season (26:4), land yielding produce (26:4-5), peace without terror (26:6), military sufficiency (26:7-8), and population growth (26:9). None of these are mere prosperity-gospel perks — they are the signs that the covenant relationship is functioning and that the curse of the Fall is being reversed within the covenant community. The agricultural abundance of verse 5 — threshing running into grape-gathering, grape-gathering into sowing — depicts a land so productive that harvests cannot keep up with each other. The climax, however, is not agricultural but relational: 'I will make My dwelling among you... I will walk among you and be your God, and you shall be My people' (26:11-12). This is the covenant formula appearing at its fullest — the template for every 'God with His people' statement in Scripture, from the Tabernacle to the New Jerusalem (Revelation 21:3). The blessings are not ends in themselves; they are evidence that the supreme blessing — the presence of God — is operational."
