          "title": "The restoration clause — covenant memory triumphing over covenant failure (26:40-45)",
          "body": "After twenty-six verses of escalating curse, the chapter turns on a single conditional: 'if they confess their iniquity' (26:40). The required posture is threefold: confession of personal and ancestral sin (26:40), acknowledgment of their hostile walking against God (26:40), and a humbled — literally 'uncircumcised' — heart (26:41). The 'uncircumcised heart' language is arresting: Israel's covenant sign was circumcision (Genesis 17), but here the heart can remain uncircumcised while the flesh is circumcised. Jeremiah 4:4 and Deuteronomy 30:6 use the same metaphor — genuine covenant membership requires the inward reality the outward sign points to. God's response to this genuine humbling is covenant-memory: 'I will remember My covenant with Jacob, and I will remember also My covenant with Isaac, and My covenant with Abraham as well, and I will remember the land' (26:42). The reverse order — Jacob, Isaac, Abraham — is the Exodus order (reversing the historical sequence) and emphasizes that the covenant grounding predates Israel's entire history of failure. Verse 44 is the chapter's most unconditional statement: 'I will not reject them, nor will I so abhor them as to destroy them, breaking My covenant with them; for I am the LORD their God.' The reason given is not Israel's repentance but God's identity — 'for I am the LORD their God.' The covenant holds because of who God is, not because of what Israel does."
